Among the hundreds of underwater places I've seen, a handful of these landscapes have deeply moved me.
I saw the first of these landscapes about 10 years ago, off the wild and rugged coast of South Africa.
Every summer, massive schools of sardines move northward, a mass migration phenomenon known as the Sardine Run.
A frenzied race of these fish
where hordes of hungry and agile predators chase them.
Common dolphins hunt together, managing to isolate sardines from the main school and creating smaller schools.
They dive and trap the fish upwards, against the surface, and rush to enjoy their wriggling feast.
The sharks follow closely.
For many people, sharks and dolphins are sworn enemies, but during the Sardine Run, they coexist.
In fact, the dolphins help the sharks feed more efficiently.
Without the dolphins, the schools created are more scattered, and the sharks often end up with a "sardine doughnut" or a mouthful of water.
I've had some lively moments with sharks during the Sardine Run, but I know they don't see me as prey.
I take my hits and am jostled like all the other participants in this scrappy feast.
Let's leave the African shores, heading east across the vastness of the Indian Ocean to the Maldives, an archipelago of coral islands.
During monsoon season, manta rays from across the entire archipelago head toward a tiny islet in Baa Atoll called Hanifaru.
Armies of crustaceans, most smaller than a marble, form the staple diet of manta rays.
When plankton concentrations are low, manta rays feed alone, performing back loops repeatedly, much like a puppy chasing its tail.
When the plankton density increases, the rays line up in single file and form these long chains. Every tasty morsel that escapes the first ray is gobbled up by the second or the one after.
When the plankton concentration reaches its peak, the manta rays swim ever closer in a rotational movement through which they feed.
As they whirl in this tight formation, the column of manta rays creates its own vortex, drawing and delivering the plankton straight into the cavernous mouths of the rays.
The experience of diving among these countless rays is absolutely unforgettable.
The first time I photographed Hanifaru, the site was unprotected and threatened by development.
I have worked with NGOs like the Manta Trust, and my photographs have contributed to making Hanifaru a protected marine area.
Fishers from neighboring islands were hunting these manta rays, using their skin to make traditional drums.
Today, they are the most ardent conservationists and the manta rays contribute over 8 million dollars to the Maldivian economy each year.
