Not long ago, I was working on a project in Baja California for National Geographic.
Halfway down the Pacific coast lies San Ignacio Lagoon, where the gray whale comes to give birth.
For a century, this coast was the site of a systematic massacre, with over 20,000 gray whales killed, leaving only a few hundred survivors.
Today, the descendants of those same whales play at the surface with their offspring, and they even interact with us.
This species has remarkably survived.
